				<div id=3D"bodyContent" class=3D"vector-body" aria-labelledby=3D"firstH=
eading" data-mw-ve-target-container=3D"">
					<div class=3D"vector-body-before-content">
							<div class=3D"mw-indicators">
		</div>

						<div id=3D"siteSub" class=3D"noprint">From Wikipedia, the free encycl=
opedia</div>
					</div>
					<div id=3D"contentSub"><div id=3D"mw-content-subtitle"></div></div>
				=09
				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Uni=
t of volume of wood</div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Cord_of_wood.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upl=
oad.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c7/Cord_of_wood.jpg/330px-Cord_=
of_wood.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"300" height=3D"225" class=3D"mw-fi=
le-element" data-file-width=3D"1200" data-file-height=3D"900"></a><figcapti=
on>A cord of wood</figcaption></figure>
<p>The <b>cord</b> is a unit of measure of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Dry_measure" title=3D"Dry measure">dry</a> <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Volume" title=3D"Volume">volume</a> used to measure <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Firewood" title=3D"Firewood">firewood</=
a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pulpwood" title=3D"Pulpwood=
">pulpwood</a> in the United States and Canada.
</p><p>A cord is the amount of wood that, when "racked and well stowed" (ar=
ranged so pieces are aligned, parallel, touching, and compact), occupies a =
volume of 128 cubic feet (3.62&nbsp;m<sup>3</sup>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cord_(unit)#cit=
e_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> This corresponds to a well-stacked woodpile 4 feet (12=
2&nbsp;cm) high, 8 feet (244&nbsp;cm) wide, and 4 feet (122&nbsp;cm) deep; =
or any other arrangement of linear measurements that yields the same volume=
.
</p><p>The name <i>cord</i> probably comes from the use of a <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rope" title=3D"Rope">cord or string</a> to measu=
re it.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Cord_(unit)#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <b>face cord</b> is a unit of volume for stacked firewood, 4 fee=
t (122&nbsp;cm) high, 8 feet (244&nbsp;cm) wide, and 16 inches (41&nbsp;cm)=
 deep=E2=80=94equal to 1/3 of a cord.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cord_(unit)#cite_note-3"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> The symbol for the unit is <b>fc - cd</b>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Cardar=
elli_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cord=
_(unit)#cite_note-Cardarelli-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definitions">Definitions</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCord_(unit)&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Definitions"><span>=
edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In Canada, the cord is legally defined by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Measurement_Canada" title=3D"Measurement Canada">Measurement Can=
ada</a>. The cord is one of three legal standards for the sale of firewood =
in Canada: stacked cubic meter (or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Stere" title=3D"Stere">stere</a>), cubic foot, and cord.
</p><p>In the United States, the cord is defined by <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Statute" title=3D"Statute">statute</a> in most states. Th=
e U.S. National Institute of Standards and Technology Handbook 130, section=
 2.4.1.2,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Cord_(unit)#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> defines a cord and pr=
ovides uniform regulations for the sale of fireplace and stove wood. In the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_system" title=3D"Metric sy=
stem">metric system</a>, wood is usually measured in <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Stere" title=3D"Stere">steres</a> and <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cubic_metre" title=3D"Cubic metre">cubic meters</a>:=
 1&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stere" title=3D"Stere">ste=
re</a> =3D 1&nbsp;m<sup>3</sup> =E2=89=88 0.276&nbsp;cords.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maine" title=3D"Maine">Main=
e</a> appears unique among U.S. states by also defining a "loose thrown cor=
d" or pile of cut firewood: "A cord of 12 or 16 inches (30 or 41&nbsp;cm) i=
n length shall mean the amount of wood, bark, and air contained in a space =
of 180 cubic feet (5.1&nbsp;m<sup>3</sup>); and a cord of wood 24 inches (6=
1&nbsp;cm) in length shall mean the amount of wood, bark, and air contained=
 in a space of 195 cubic feet (5.5&nbsp;m<sup>3</sup>). [1981, c.&nbsp;219 =
(amd).]"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Cord_(unit)#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Other non-official terms for firewood volume include <i>standing cor=
d</i>, <i>kitchen cord</i>, <i>running cord</i>, <i><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Face_cord" title=3D"Face cord">face cord</a></i>, <i>fenc=
ing cord</i>, <i>country cord</i>, <i>long cord</i>, and <i><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_unusual_units_of_measurement#Cord_and_ric=
k" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"List of unusual units of measurement">ric=
k</a></i>, all subject to local variation. These are usually taken to mean =
a well-stacked pile of wood in which the logs are shorter or longer than in=
 a legal cord, to accommodate various burners. For example, a face cord com=
monly consists of wood that is 16 inches (41&nbsp;cm) long.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cord_(u=
nit)#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The volume of a face cord therefore is typical=
ly 1/3 of the volume of a full cord even though it is 8 feet (244&nbsp;cm) =
long and 4 feet (122&nbsp;cm) high. A face cord is also called a <i>rick</i=
> in the midwestern United States.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cord_(unit)#cite_note-8"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p><p>The term is used in other English-speaking countries, such as New Ze=
aland,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Cord_(unit)#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> but may not have a legal=
 definition.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Heating_value">Heating valu=
e</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCord_(unit=
)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Heating value">=
<span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span>=
</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article=
: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Firewood#Heating_value" title=3D=
"Firewood">Firewood =C2=A7&nbsp;Heating value</a></div>
<p>One seasoned (dry) cord of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quer=
cus_rubra" title=3D"Quercus rubra">Northern red oak</a> with a heating valu=
e of 22.1&nbsp;million <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_the=
rmal_unit" title=3D"British thermal unit">British thermal units</a> per <a =
class=3D"mw-selflink selflink">cord</a> (23.3&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Gigajoule" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gigajoule">GJ</a=
>/cord) has the heating equivalent of 159 U.S. gallons (132 imperial gallon=
s; 602 liters) of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fuel_oil" title=
=3D"Fuel oil">fuel oil</a> with a heating value of 138,700 British thermal =
units per U.S. gallon (38.7 megajoules per liter).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cord_(unit)#cit=
e_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cord_(unit)#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Australia">Australia</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCord_(unit)&amp;ac=
tion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Australia"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Until <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metrication_in_Australia"=
 title=3D"Metrication in Australia">metrication in Australia</a>, an imperi=
al cord was a measurement for wood and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Firewood" title=3D"Firewood">firewood</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cord_(unit)#cite_n=
ote-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cord_(unit)#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The meas=
urements for a cord of wood were 4&nbsp;feet high by 8&nbsp;feet wide by 4&=
nbsp;feet deep, or usually a stack of wood containing 128&nbsp;cubic feet (=
cu ft). The imperial cord enclosed 128&nbsp;cu ft.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cord_(unit)#cit=
e_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cord_(unit)#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"France">France</h2><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCord_(unit)&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: France"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <i>corde</i> was a unit of volume used before metrication in several=
 French-speaking countries (France, Belgium and Luxembourg). Its value vari=
ed from 2=E2=80=935 steres (71=E2=80=93177&nbsp;cu&nbsp;ft) depending on th=
e region. <sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cord_(unit)#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cord_(un=
it)#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
